  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_809810318" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/809810318" />
    <a title="Terry" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9852546-terry"><img alt="Terry" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1342846769p2/9852546.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/809810318?book_show_action=true">Jan 02, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Terry" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Terry" href="/user/show/9852546-terry">Terry</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer809810318" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13547348753796063865">Things I&apos;ve come to appreciate:<br/>• Washington politics had just as much vitriol in Lincoln&apos;s day as today. The book tells of a congressman who beat another congressman with a cane until crippled, an act his public praised. Also, a congressman fired a pistol at another at point blank range. This charge didn&apos;t go off.<br/>• The American public was just as divided in Lincoln&apos;s day regarding slavery as today&apos;s public is about issues of our time. Abolitionists wanted to the South to be governed by blacks an</span>
  <span id="freeText13547348753796063865" style="display:none">Things I've come to appreciate:<br />• Washington politics had just as much vitriol in Lincoln's day as today. The book tells of a congressman who beat another congressman with a cane until crippled, an act his public praised. Also, a congressman fired a pistol at another at point blank range. This charge didn't go off.<br />• The American public was just as divided in Lincoln's day regarding slavery as today's public is about issues of our time. Abolitionists wanted to the South to be governed by blacks and confederates hung while slave state leaders thought of horses and slaves as being equal property. Lincoln displayed amazing leadership by bringing these people together. Crucially, he had the support of the populace while his fellow politicians and many newspapers held him in great distain.<br />• The Lincoln-Douglas debates had the first speaker present for 60 minutes, the second speaker for 90, and then the first again for 30 minutes. Although there was no amplification and the events were held in inclement weather, the public eagerly attended. How many would do this today?<br />• Lincoln came from an unusual geographic perspective, a time and place where his American youth was surrounded by real wilderness and wilderness values. The nation doesn't have this dichotomy between city and rural anymore. The wilderness shaped his honest values.<br />• Some of the generals in the early war, particularly McClellan, were detrimental to Union effort. In contrast, the confederates did very well with Lee. Lee was against slavery but for Virginia. Ultimately the relationship between Lincoln, Grant, and Sherman was important in the Union success.<br />• Perhaps naively, I don't think war is a barbarous now. Then, brothers were fighting each other. Combatants were within view of each other and often clubbed or stabbed each other. Long marches ended by sleeping in wet blankets. Surgery involved saws with little understanding of infection.<br /><br />I wanted to read Lincoln's biography after watching Team of Rivals but thought Sandburg's talents as a writer and poet would offer a different perspective. The writing isn't especially captivating, its a long read, but the subject makes up for this.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13547348753796063865" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

