    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1973334790" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1973334790" />
    <a title="Ryan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/675969-ryan"><img alt="Ryan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1421238275p2/675969.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1973334790?book_show_action=true">Aug 22, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ryan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ryan" href="/user/show/675969-ryan">Ryan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1973334790" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14479249435714481333">As an Abraham Lincoln enthusiast, I can&apos;t believe that it took me this long to listen to this classic biography of our 16th president. No one who wants to know Lincoln and his legacy should skip this important work. Sandburg&apos;s respect for the &quot;tycoon&quot; certainly comes through loud and clear, but it doesn&apos;t lead to hero worship. He is fully cognizant of the President&apos;s shortcomings and weaknesses and the controversies surrounding his rise and administration. But Lincoln&apos;s almost superhuman magnani</span>
  <span id="freeText14479249435714481333" style="display:none">As an Abraham Lincoln enthusiast, I can't believe that it took me this long to listen to this classic biography of our 16th president. No one who wants to know Lincoln and his legacy should skip this important work. Sandburg's respect for the "tycoon" certainly comes through loud and clear, but it doesn't lead to hero worship. He is fully cognizant of the President's shortcomings and weaknesses and the controversies surrounding his rise and administration. But Lincoln's almost superhuman magnanimity and his genuine goodness still prevails. This comprehensive biography is early enough that it doesn't suffer from the modern inclinations to reinvent Lincoln in some "novel" way in order to garner some new niche in the historical academic world or the marketplace. Only those who have read at least half a dozen books on Lincoln and/or the Civil War can start to appreciate the pattern of Lincoln's goodness and genius that begins to emerge from our historical interpretation of the past. I strongly recommend this biography as a good starting place.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14479249435714481333" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


